// T1138: returning a borrowed (non-`move`) Optional-wrapped single-owner handle
// (Mutex[int]?/task[int]?) as owned used to segfault — dupOptionalVectorElem has
// no clone for these and shared the one handle, so the source local and the
// caller's result both dropped it (double-free). Sibling gap to T1102, which
// only matched BARE handles.
//
// The ownership pass now rejects the unsound forms at compile time (the T1138
// fix makes the rejection see through Optional layers):
//   pass_opt(Mutex[int]? m) Mutex[int]? { return m; }            // direct return
//   pass_opt(Mutex[int]? m) Mutex[int]? { Mutex[int]? x = m; return x; } // laundered
// Those are covered by Go ownership tests (cannot return/move borrowed param).
//
// Two related shapes remain broken and OUT OF SCOPE for T1138 — both route
// through the same unfixable dupOptionalVectorElem codegen path when ownership
// cannot see the handle: `Mutex[int]?? x = m; return x;` / consuming the wrapped
// value (T1212), and a generic fn returning an Optional-wrapped handle param
// (T1213). Do NOT add runtime tests for those until they are fixed.
//
// These runtime tests prove the T1138 fix does NOT over-reject the valid paths
// and that they stay leak-free.
worker() int {
  return 42;
}

// Valid: a `move` Optional-wrapped task param transfers the single handle's
// ownership to the caller's result — no aliasing, no double-free.
pass_move_opt(task[int]? move t) task[int]? {
  return t;
}

t1138_move_optional_task_return() `test {
  task[int]? t = go worker();
  task[int]? r = pass_move_opt(move t);
  int v = <-r!;
  assert(v == 42, "move optional-task return");
}

// Valid: a `move` Optional-wrapped Mutex param — parity for the other handle.
pass_move_mutex(Mutex[int]? move m) Mutex[int]? {
  return m;
}

t1138_move_optional_mutex_return() `test {
  Mutex[int]? m = Mutex[int](7);
  Mutex[int]? r = pass_move_mutex(move m);
  int v = r!.lock().borrow;
  assert(v == 7, "move optional-mutex return");
}

// Valid: the non-escaping Some-wrap coercion `Mutex[int]?? x = m` materializes a
// fresh outer Optional wrapper rather than aliasing the source handle, and its
// drop does not recurse into the borrowed inner — the wrap-depth carve-out runs
// before the single-owner reject, so this stays valid and leak-free.
wrap_coerce(Mutex[int]? m) {
  Mutex[int]?? x = m;
}

t1138_wrap_coerce_optional_mutex() `test {
  Mutex[int]? m = Mutex[int](9);
  wrap_coerce(m);
  int v = m!.lock().borrow;
  assert(v == 9, "source mutex still usable after wrap-coerce borrow");
}

// Valid: a `move` Optional-wrapped handle laundered through an owned local before
// return — `move` makes the param owned, so the var-decl `x = m` is a real move
// (not the rejected borrow-alias), and the single handle transfers cleanly to the
// caller's result. The reject is gated on Borrowed state, so this fragile combo
// (launder + optional + handle) must stay valid and leak-free.
pass_move_launder(Mutex[int]? move m) Mutex[int]? {
  Mutex[int]? x = m;
  return x;
}

t1138_move_launder_optional_mutex() `test {
  Mutex[int]? m = Mutex[int](11);
  Mutex[int]? r = pass_move_launder(move m);
  int v = r!.lock().borrow;
  assert(v == 11, "move-launder optional-mutex return");
}
